        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-06T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-06T18:00:00-05:00" n="69"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d69">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.8411/10–2444: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-06T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >November 6, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>161. Department has been discussing the subject of your 214, October 24, with the
                    British Embassy.<note n="22" xml:id="d69fn22">Conversations concerning the
                        British claim to control the Ogaden and the reserved areas were held between
                        the Chief of the Division of African Affairs (Villard) and Mr. John Russell,
                        Second Secretary of the British Embassy, on October 30 and November 4, 1944.
                        The information received by Mr. Villard in these conversations corresponded
                        to that received from the Legation in Ethiopia. Memoranda of the
                        conversations were received in the Legation on November 22.</note> Further
                    word will be sent you shortly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
